The Ministry of
Health (MoH) on Friday announced that 502 people tested positive for COVID-19
out of a sample size of 3,503 tested in the last 24 hours, raising the
positivity rate to 15.4 per cent. Of the
cases, 456 are Kenyans while 46 are foreigners; 261 are males and
241 are females. The youngest case is that of a one-year-old child and the oldest patient is 93 years old. Total confirmed
positive cases are now 331,539 with 3,738,841 cumulative tests having been
conducted so far. The infections were
distributed across various counties as follows: Nairobi (286), Kiambu (37),
Nyeri (31), Machakos (19), Murang’a (18), Siaya (18), Kilifi (15), Nakuru (13),
Kericho (11), Kirinyaga (8), Kitui (7), Mombasa (7), Tana River (7), Kajiado
(5), Garissa (4), Nyandarua (3), Uasin Gishu (3), Kakamega (2), Kisii (2) and
Kisumu (2). Bungoma, Busia, Taita Taveta and West Pokot recorded a single case
each. According to Health
Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe, 280 patients have recovered from the disease
which has claimed no lives in the past 24 hours. Cumulative fatalities
currently stand at 5,651. "There are 99
patients currently admitted in our health facilities, while 3,513 are under the
Home-Based Isolation and Care program," said Kagwe. "2 patients
are in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU) and are on ventilator support, while 16
are in General Wards and are on supplemental oxygen. No patient is in the High
Dependency Unit (HDU)." A total of
18,696,980 vaccines have also been administered across the country, according
to Kagwe. "Of these,
16,702,410 are doses administered to the adult population (18 years and above).
Another 1,514,784 are doses administered to those between 15 to 17 years,
41,395 are below 15 years but above 12 years while 438,391 are booster
doses," said Kagwe. "The total
number of vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 23,536 while the total
number of people fully vaccinated in the last 24 hours is 8,779."